[2] Brazil (Mato Grosso)
Date: Sun 19 Apr 2009
Source: O Globo [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://oglobo.globo.com/cidades/mat/2009/04/19/vigilancia-sanitaria-investiga-decima-morte-por-suspeita-dengue-hemorragica-em-mato-grosso-755343024.asp>


According to the state [Mato Grosso] Secretariat of Health, up to the
present 10 fatal cases suspected of DHF have been registered. Of
these, 3 have been [laboratory] confirmed. The cases under
investigation occurred in Cuiaba, Varzea Grande, Nova Nazare, Rosario
Oeste, and Tangara da Serra. The total number of cases in the state
[in 2009] is 353.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Another report cited in ProMED-PORT (archive no. 20090422.1515)
gives the total number of dengue cases in Mato Grosso for 2009 as
536. - Mod.TY]

******
[3] Argentina (Santa Fe)
Date: Thu 23 Apr 2009
Source: Notife.com, Rosario3 report [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.notife.com/noticia/articulo/967493/Cappiello_afirmo_que_el_brote_del_dengue_entro_en_una_meseta_.html>


Dengue is controlled, but we have to ["bust"] the mosquito [that
transmits dengue virus]. This was the statement put forward by the
Santa Fe Minister of Health, Miguel Angel Cappiello this Thursday [23
Apr 2009] after stating that the number of people ill [with dengue]
remains at about 650 in the entire area [of the state].

Within this framework, one emphasizing that prevention and the public
awareness campaign continue, he summarized the objective of this year
[2009] with a curious sentence: "The expression may sound vulgar, but
we must break the [mosquito's] balls in winter to prevent dengue in
summer," he stated.

The same message [that dengue cases have reached a plateau] was
conveyed independently by Mayor Miguel Lifschitz -- despite new
dengue cases ... -- when he stated, "the peak of the infection has
passed."

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The 21 Apr 2009 edition of El Diario
(<http://www.diario.com.mx/nota.php?notaid=ceb2d807d9cee742a6832f83354eb5b9>,
in Spanish) indicated that the Ministry of Health reported that the
northern region and in particular the provinces of Chaco, Salta, and
Catamarca, has been the most affected by the epidemic which totals 17
856 locally acquired dengue cases so far in 2009 in the entire
country. That article also reported that 2 babies were infected with
dengue in utero.

[A map showing the location of the provinces in Argentina ca be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/argentina_pol96.jpg>.
A HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Argentina can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/r/00aA>. - Mod.TY]

