[4] The Americas
Date: Fri 17 Apr 2009
Source: Pan American Health Organization Update on Dengue in the
Americas, Epidemiological Alerts 6(9) [edited]
<http://new.paho.org/hq/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1243&Itemid=211>


Current situation of dengue in the Americas, April 2009
-------------------------------------------------------
Dengue is an endemic disease in most of the countries of the
Americas. Over the past 20 years, it has shown sustained cycles of
outbreaks every 3-5 years.

From 1 Jan [2009] -- epidemiological week (EW) 15, 2009 (16 Apr
2009), a total of 234 106 cases of dengue have been reported,
including 3778 cases of severe dengue (dengue hemorrhagic fever,
dengue shock syndrome, and complicated dengue) and 74 deaths, with a
regional fatality rate of 1.90 percent.

To date, 36 percent (n = 25) of the total number of deaths has been
concentrated in Bolivia, followed by Brazil, where 34 percent of the
deaths occurred (n = 25).

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A table in this report shows the data reported by each subregion in
the Americas according to the data reported to date by the Ministries
of Health of the countries to the PAHO/WHO Regional dengue team.
Rates calculated are based on the population at risk in each country.
- Mod.TY]

